terraform.dev-202601012002.20.functions.7

test(terraform): document string template type coercion edge case

Adds example 7 demonstrating an unexpected behavior in Terraform/OpenTofu
where string templates `"${var.number}"` preserve the original type
rather than converting to string. A numeric variable interpolated alone
in a string template remains a number (5 == "${var.number}"), but
concatenation with other text forces string conversion
("instance-5" == "instance-${var.number}").

This builds on the comprehensive function examples from commit ff3406d,
adding a seventh category focused on type conversion pitfalls. Unlike
examples 1-6 which demonstrate expected function behavior, this example
warns about a subtle edge case that can cause hard-to-debug type
mismatch errors if code lacks proper unit test coverage.

The test suite validates three key behaviors:
- Bare numeric interpolation preserves number type (5 == "${var.default}")
- Explicit tostring() ensures string conversion (tostring(5) == "5")
- String concatenation forces automatic coercion ("instance-${5}" is string)
- Boolean values exhibit identical coercion behavior

Recommends using explicit tostring() in critical path code to prevent
type confusion bugs. The README links to OpenTofu documentation on type
systems and conversion rules for developers who need deeper understanding
of the evaluation semantics.

